We first calculate the three ratios as follows:

1. ROE (Return on Equity):  
 • Use the average owner’s equity. Here, the beginning owner’s equity is the Paid‑in Capital (13,000,000.00) and the ending owner’s equity is given as 14,167,783.63.  
 • Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 14,167,783.63) / 2 = 13,583,891.815  
 • Net Profit (from the income statement) = 1,167,783.63  
 • ROE = (1,167,783.63 ÷ 13,583,891.815) × 100 ≈ 8.60%

2. Debt to Asset Ratio:  
 • This is calculated as Total Liabilities / Total Assets.  
 • From the balance sheet, Total Liabilities (here, only Current Liabilities appear) = 631,880.98  
 • Total Assets = 14,799,664.61  
 • Debt to Asset Ratio = 631,880.98 ÷ 14,799,664.61 ≈ 0.0427, which rounds to 0.04

3. Gross Profit Margin:  
 • This is calculated as Gross Profit / Total Revenue × 100  
 • From the income statement, Gross Profit = 2,060,619.40 and Total Revenue = 3,397,619.40  
 • Gross Profit Margin = (2,060,619.40 ÷ 3,397,619.40) × 100 ≈ 60.61%

Thus, the final solution is:
{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "8.60%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.04",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "60.61%"
  }
}
